  "prompt": "Is money laundering unlawful?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is unlawful in virtually all jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering is the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This typically involves three stages:\n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing the illicit funds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering**: Conducting a series of transactions to obscure the origin of the funds.\n3. **Integration**: Making the funds appear legitimate by integrating them into the economy through normal financial or business activities.\n\nLaws against money laundering are designed to prevent criminals from disguising the origins of their illegal activities, such as drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, and terrorism financing. These laws typically require financial institutions and other regulated entities to implement robust anti-money laundering (AML) programs, report suspicious activities, and maintain thorough records of transactions.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including significant fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. International bodies like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) work to develop and promote policies to combat money laundering globally, and many countries have established their own AML regulations in line with these international standards.",
